  <div class="row">
      <div class="col-md-6">
      <!--<div class="Materials"></div>-->
      <h2>Materials:</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>8 x 6 sticky notes</li>
        <li>Sharpie Markers</li>
        <li>Wall Space or Brown Paper</li>
        <li>Preferred: Sticky Note Easel Pad (25x30 inches) </li>
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-6">
       <!--<div class="Set-up"></div>-->
      <h2>Set Up:</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>Put the Easel Pad sheet on the Wall Space or Brown Paper </li>
        <li>Write down a Hypotheses Statement Template on the Easel Pad</li>
        <ul>
        <li>We Believe __(WHO)____ </li>
        <li>Will __(WHAT)_______ </li>
        <li>Because __(Why)_______ </li>
        </ul>
        <li>Research <a href="https://www.stevebizblog.com/have-you-defined-your-leap-or-faith-assumptions/">Leap of Faith Assumptions</a> as it will be important when deciding which hypothesis is most important.</li>
        </ol>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-md-12">
     <!--<div class="Instructions"></div>-->
     <h2>Intructions:</h2>
     <ol>
       <li>Consider your Customers. Did you make an assumptions about your customers. Spend some time writing some hypotheses about your customers on the 6x8 Sticky Notes</li>
       <li>Consider your Cusotmer's unmet needs. Did you make an assumptions about your Cusomter's unmet needs. Spend some time writing some hypotheses about your customer's unment needs on the 6x8 Sticky Notes</li>
       <li>Consider your proposed concepts or soltions. Did you make an assumptions. Spend some time writing some hypotheses about your proposed concepts or solutions on the 6x8 Sticky Notes</li>
       <li>Now that you have all of your assumptions documented on 6x8 stick notes, select which hypothese (or set of hypotheses) are more important to you (or the group) to prove or disprove.
       Write the prioritized hypothesis on the large easel pad. More than one hyptheses may be selected. </li>
     </ol>
   <p><br /> NOTE: Use voting dots if there is difficulty gaining consensus on more important hypotheses.</p>
     </div>
